<h1>/pause function in macros</h1>
	<B>Hi there,<P>I was wondering, is there a limit on how long the /pause function works in macros?<P>I play a monk, and was trying to make a macro that would announce when I mend, then wait the 6 minutes, then announce that mend is back up.<P>i.e.:<BR>/gsay MENDING!<BR>/pause 3600<BR>/gsay Mend is now UP!<P>However, the timer seems to reset after maybe 1~2 minutes at best.<P>I've tried:<BR>/gsay MENDING!<BR>/pause 60000<BR>/pause 60000<BR>/pause 60000<BR>/gsay Mend is now UP!<P>which should theoretically stop for 30 minutes, but it only seems to go about 3-4 minutes at best.<P>Thanks for any help you can give!<P>Genthar, Monk of Quellious.<BR>Disciples of Honor<BR>E'Ci Server</B><P>Actaully, there is a limit of 1 minute with the /pause command.  From the eqmanual_suppliment.doc:<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><P>You may now enter pauses in social batches with the /pause command.  /pause takes an argument from 1 to 600, with the value being equal to the number of tenths of seconds (i.e. /pause 100 will yield a 10 second pause).<P><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>So any number over 600, which is one minute, in the /pause argument will be seen as 600.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

Bertg wrote:<P><B>Since you can put more than one function on a line, couldn't you do a macro that says:<P>/pause 600, /say 5 minutes to go<BR>/pause 600, /say 4 minutes to go<BR>/pause 600, /say 3 minutes to go<BR>/pause 600, /say 2 minutes to go<BR>/pause 600, /say 1 minute to go<P>You're limited to 5 lines on a macros, I think, so you just have to start paying attention to the mend button for the last minute until it pops.</B><P>Thanks for the tip.  Commas can be used to separate commands on the same line.<P>Alan<BR>

<hr>

<B>Two small corrections:<P>1. Commas can only be used if the /pause command is the first command on the line.  Really would love to double-up many other commands, but it currently only works for pause.   <IMG SRC="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/frown.gif"><P>2. Unless this was changed recently, the problem with using Pause in the manner mentioned here is that pausing during a Social locks you out of using other Socials until the first Social is finished.  As most people have Socials for /assist, /loc, and pulling calls, this could be a problem for them.<P>Corinus<BR>Cazic-Thule</B><P>Thanks.  And, yes, as far as I know you can only run one macro at a time.  A paused macro is still running, and socials are macros.  So be careful using pauses in your macros.<P>Alan<BR>



